In the figure, the length of side $AB$ of square $ABCD$ is $10$ and $BE=2$. What is the area of the inner square $EFGH$?
{{IMG:328614208531304e.png}}
$\textbf{(A)}\ 90-16\sqrt{6}\qquad\textbf{(B)}\ 100-16\sqrt{6}\qquad\textbf{(C)}\ 100+16\sqrt{6}\qquad\textbf{(D)}\ 110-16\sqrt{6}\qquad\textbf{(E)}\ 120-16\sqrt{6}$

In the coordinate plane, consider pentagon $ABCDE$ with vertices $A(2,2), B(0,2), C(-2,0), D(0,-2),$ and $E(2,0)$. You are given five transformations:
- $P$, a rotation of $72^{\circ}$ counterclockwise around the origin;
- $Q$, a rotation of $72^{\circ}$ clockwise around the origin;
- $X$, a reflection across the $x$-axis;
- $Y$, a reflection across the $y$-axis;
- $XY$, a reflection across the line $y=x$.
Determine the number of sequences of $40$ transformations chosen from this set that will return all vertices of the pentagon to their initial positions.
$\textbf{(A)}\ 5^{18}$   
$\textbf{(B)}\ 5^{19}$   
$\textbf{(C)}\ 5^{20}$   
$\textbf{(D)}\ 5^{21}$   
$\textbf{(E)}\ 5^{22}$
